<br>
 For example: If you have Word open and the Japanese IME is enabled (and it shows it in the bottom right) and you click on another window, say a web site that doesn't support the IME, the Japanese IME icon will disappear in the bottom right and it will revert back to EN. But, if you click back on Word, it should re-enable, because Word supports it.<br>
<br>
 For me, with Windows 98, the icon disappears when I'm using a program that doesn't support the Japanese IME. I'm pretty sure that's what's happening with yours, also.<br>
<br>
 Try going into Word, or even on this BBS, and then try to enable it. Then open Solitare, and see if you can select it. <br>
<br>
 In summary: You have to be typing somewhere where the Japanese IME is supported. Otherwise, you won't be able to select it from the icon on the toolbar.<br>
<br>
 At least, that's how it works to my understanding. <br>
<br>
 - Yuri <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/1/03 6:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=949.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Japanese Fonts</span><hr size=1> sinfire,<br>
<br>
actually the process for windows XP is different than for the other OS's.  XP is the first microsoft OS to fully and natively support japanese.  This means you don't need a bunch of clunky work-arounds to input and read japanese on the computer.  In addition, the OS will display dialog boxes, program windows, etc. in japanese (in previous versions of windows, while you could input japanese, non-japanese versions would display screwed up dialog boxes and stuff for japanese programs).  Furthermore the file system natively supports japanese file names, so you can name your folders/files etc. using kanji and whatnot.<br>
<br>
That having been said, the floating toolbar is also cool, because you don't encounter the problems that uglywhitekid mentioned above (i.e. with it disappearing - it remains onscreen all the time, though you can make it transparent).  This is because you can input japanese at all times using windows XP (unlike win98 etc.)<br>
<br>
at any rate: first check to see if you have the IME active in the lower right hand corner.  If you see the following icon (JP) right-click on it and select &quot;restore the Language Bar&quot;.  Refer to the picture below:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/language/2languagebar.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
It should stay floating on top from then on.<br>
<br>
OR.... if you don't have that JP icon in the lower right hand corner, you will need to go to [START MENU] &gt; [Control Panel] &gt; [Regional and Language Options] &gt; [Languages (tab)] &gt;  [Details]:<br>
then see if Japanese is installed as the default language (in the first drop down menu) if you so desire.  Then see if the IME is installed (in the open area below the menu).  It should read something like &quot;<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Japanese</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - Microsoft natural IME standard 2002 v8.1&quot; and perhaps also &quot;Microsoft Natural Input 2002 v.8.1&quot;.  If not, click [add] then add the appropriate inputs.  <br>
<br>
i you like, after you finish with the languages&gt;[details] submenu, you can set your &quot;regional&quot; options to Japanese (under the [Regional Options(tab)] in the previous menu) and the default non-unicode matching character set to &quot;japanese&quot; under the [Advanced (tab)].  Be warned that doing this will make a lot of MS services like messenger automatically download the japanese version (so if you download messenger, it will automatically default to downloading the japanese version, though you can change this manually of course!)  So things like the &quot;media&quot; tab in IE will default to the japanese version, and going to google.com will automatically bring you to the japanese version and so on.  For me, this is pretty convinient, but it's up to you.  If you decided you don't like it, you can always change your default &quot;region&quot; back from japanese.  Oh yes, and the time will display in japanese 24hr time, etc.<br>
<br>
anyway, after you're done with all that, you should be able to input japanese.  reactivate the floating language bar as detailed above and happy typing!  If you want more info about some of the other advanced features of the XP language bar, you could check out the post above about directly inputting kanji into your computer using a mouse or a tablet.<br>
<br>
hope that helps! <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/panda/panda3.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu.  <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
